    <p class="note">The series opens with <strong>A1 &mdash; Why an Agile Agent Workflow</strong>, then climbs the
      ladder. The companion course, <a href={PortalWeb.deep_link_base() <> "/elixir/course"}>Functional Programming in Elixir</a>, builds the
      Portal&rsquo;s Elixir and OTP foundations that this workflow puts to work.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="exemplar">
    <h2>Portal Exemplar &middot; A7</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Everything the six chapters teach converges here. Portal is built the way the course prescribes &mdash; one
        value ladder per chapter, each rung decomposed into stories, planned in a roadmap, defined in a spec, briefed
        to a Claude agent, and accepted only when its invariants hold &mdash; and carried from an empty repository to a
        clustered, deployed platform. The exemplar is seven steps, each run through the same loop.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bridge">
      <div class="cell idea">
        <span class="lbl">the workflow</span>
        <p>Decompose into stories, plan a roadmap, write the spec and the agent brief, build, and prove &mdash; correct
          by definition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</div>
      <div class="cell elix">
        <span class="lbl">Portal, in production</span>
        <p>A branded store, an event-sourced engine behind one facade, a web application, a bot, and a dashboard
          &mdash; supervised, gated, and live.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <dl class="deflist" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
      <dt>A7.01</dt><dd>The starting line: the branded store &mdash; the given foundation and branded Snowflake ids.</dd>
      <dt>A7.02</dt><dd>The engine &mdash; a supervised, event-sourced core behind one facade, built end to end.</dd>
      <dt>A7.03</dt><dd>The web &mdash; contexts, server-rendered pages, LiveView, real-time, auth, and deployment.</dd>
      <dt>A7.04</dt><dd>A second surface: the Telegram bot &mdash; a parallel surface over the same facade.</dd>
      <dt>A7.05</dt><dd>The student dashboard &mdash; a new domain dimension, entitlements, where paid becomes unlocked.</dd>
      <dt>A7.06</dt><dd>Shipping to production &mdash; releases, runtime configuration, clustering, and migrations.</dd>
      <dt>A7.07</dt><dd>Retrospective &mdash; what the workflow bought, and where human judgement still decided.</dd>
    </dl>

    <p class="take">From zero to production is not a slogan here &mdash; it is the seven steps above, each carried
      through the same loop the six chapters teach.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="refs">
    <h2>References</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The canon this course distils and extends, grouped by the workflow layer it informs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="refs">
      <h3>Stories, specifications &amp; acceptance</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.mountaingoatsoftware.com/books/user-stories-applied">Cohn, M. &mdash; <em>User Stories Applied</em></a> &mdash; the story form, INVEST, and splitting.</li>
        <li><a href="https://gojko.net/books/specification-by-example/">Adzic, G. &mdash; <em>Specification by Example</em></a> &mdash; living documentation that cannot drift.</li>
        <li><a href="https://cucumber.io/docs/gherkin/reference/">Gherkin &mdash; Given / When / Then</a> &mdash; executable acceptance scenarios.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Agile delivery and iteration</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/extreme-programming-explained/0201616416/">Beck, K. &mdash; <em>Extreme Programming Explained</em></a> &mdash; small batches, short loops.</li>
        <li><a href="https://pragprog.com/titles/tpp20/the-pragmatic-programmer-20th-anniversary-edition/">Hunt &amp; Thomas &mdash; <em>The Pragmatic Programmer</em></a> &mdash; tracer bullets and walking skeletons.</li>
        <li><a href="https://continuousdelivery.com/">Humble &amp; Farley &mdash; <em>Continuous Delivery</em></a> &mdash; releasing thin increments safely.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>The agent and implementation workflow</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://llmstxt.org/">The <code>llms.txt</code> convention</a> &mdash; machine-readable briefs.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/claude-code-best-practices">Anthropic &mdash; Claude Code best practices</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents">Anthropic &mdash; Building effective agents</a>.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Reliability and correctness</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://fsharpforfunandprofit.com/rop/">Wlaschin, S. &mdash; Railway Oriented Programming</a> &mdash; a closed error discipline.</li>
        <li><a href="https://lexi-lambda.github.io/blog/2019/11/05/parse-don-t-validate/">King, A. &mdash; Parse, don&rsquo;t validate</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://hexdocs.pm/stream_data/StreamData.html"><code>StreamData</code></a> &mdash; property-based testing for Elixir.</li>
      </ul>
